<2ND_LINE>AM-Black & Decker,0308</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Black & Decker Gets Financing For American Standard Bid</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOWSON, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Black & Decker Corp. announced Friday that a
group of commercial banks has arranged $2.2 billion in financing
for the company's $2.1 billion hostile takeover attempt for
American Standard Inc.
   The syndidate is composed of 19 domestic and foreign banks,
including Chase Manhattan Bank, which earlier pledged $750 million
of its own funds toward the deal, the company said.
   American Standard has vowed to fight Black & Decker's
$65-per-share bid, saying it will consider a restructuring,
leveraged buyout or a friendly merger with another company. The New
York-based manufacturer of plumbing, heating and air conditioning
equipment has urged its shareholders to reject the offer and has
adopted a ``poison pill'' plan allowing shareholders to buy back
their stock at half market value if the takeover succeeds.
   Black & Decker, which currently owns just 100 shares of the
company, launched an effort Wednesday to oust American Standard's
board of directors. Shareholders will be asked to vote their shares
to remove 10 members of the company's board, Black & Decker said.
One of the objectives, the suitor said, was to remove the poison
pill plan.
   The Towson, Md.-based tool and appliance maker also announced
the expiration of a waiting period under the Hart-Scott-Rodino
Antitrust Improvements Act of 1976. The law required a 30-day
cooling off period to check for possible antitrust violations.
   ``The screening process is over and that means there are no
antitrust implications,'' said Black & Decker spokeswoman Barbara
Lucas.
   Mrs. Lucas said the agreements with the banks are for permanent
financing of the takeover. Some of the $2.2 billion loan is for
expenses related to the deal, she said.
   Black & Decker launched its bid for American Standard on Jan. 28.
</TEXT>
